<title>The Ultimate Office Guide to Data Backup</title>
<description>Don't forget to back up your data! No, really, this is one of the most important pieces of advice we can offer. Still need help? Start with this handy guide.</description>
<link>http://www.staples.com/sbd/cre/tech-services/explore-tips-and-advice/tech-articles/the-easytech-field-guide-to-data-backup.html</link>
<media:thumbnail url="http://www.staples.com/sbd/cre/tech-services/images/res/data-backup-icon.jpg"></media:thumbnail>
<pubDate>03 Feb 2012 18:34:24 GMT</pubDate>
<content>
<![CDATA[
<blockquote>
<p>Don't forget to back up your data! No, really, this is one of the most important pieces of advice we can offer. Still need help? Start with this handy guide.</p></blockquote>

<p>Youve heard it dozens of times: Dont forget to back up your data. We admit, we tend to say it often ourselves, and for good reason. Backing up can prevent data loss in the event of hard drive failure or computer theft  and give you a little extra peace of mind. Its also easier than you might think.</p>

<p>Here are some top backup options for keeping your data safe.</p>

<h2>External Hard Drives</h2>

<p>Usually looking sleek and futuristic, external drives offer high-capacity storage and often feature automatic backup options. That means youre freed from backup tasks after initial setup, unless you want to change the settings. External drives can usually be positioned either vertically or horizontally so that they fit nicely into any desktop space.</p>

<p>
<strong>Example:</strong> A 
<a href="http://www.google.com/url?sa=t&amp;amp;rct=j&amp;amp;q=&amp;amp;esrc=s&amp;amp;source=web&amp;amp;cd=2&amp;amp;ved=0CJYBEBYwAQ&amp;amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.seagate.com%2Fexternal-hard-drives%2Fportable-hard-drives%2Fstandard%2Fgoflex%2F&amp;amp;ei=qnMFUP-sIIf20gHXu-3tCA&amp;amp;usg=AFQjCNEnSKVAcUT9kNVMNbRNNSV7Xnze8Q&amp;amp;sig2=TxUGrfAkJyLlr6ylBGsY5w">Seagate FreeAgent GoFlex</a> external hard drive comes with encryption technology to keep files safe, and allows for backup from a PC or Mac.</p>

<h2>USB Flash Drives</h2>

<p>Generally used for transporting small to moderate amounts of data, USB flash drives are perfect for transferring photos, videos and other files between computers. Theyre small  one can fit in the palm of your hand or on your key ring  and affordable. USB flash drives are a convenient option for storing photos from a vacation, or all the files involved in a certain work project.</p>

<p>
<strong>Example: </strong>A
<strong> </strong>
<a href="http://www.google.com/url?sa=t&amp;amp;rct=j&amp;amp;q=&amp;amp;esrc=s&amp;amp;source=web&amp;amp;cd=1&amp;amp;ved=0CGYQFjAA&amp;amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.sandisk.com%2Fproducts%2Fusb-flash-drives%2Fcruzer-usb-flash-drive&amp;amp;ei=y3MFUKKUCOHb0QHAnbTbCA&amp;amp;usg=AFQjCNHUGssYYBu2pwAm92KRe6NQTF4qvg&amp;amp;sig2=wyqnN8I911Ynik2oC9mjKQ">SanDisk Cruzer</a> USB flash drive comes in different capacities, from 4GB to 64GB, and includes secure software that keeps files protected.</p>

<h2>Network Attached Storage</h2>

<p>For small companies or homes with multiple computers, network attached storage (NAS) is a good option because it can centralize storage functions. Rather than getting external drives for each computer, everyone can back up to the same location, which also facilitates document and printer sharing. These storage options are often packed with other advantages as well, such as simple uploading and plug-and-play setup.</p>

<p>
<strong>Example:</strong>
<em> </em>
<a href="http://www.google.com/url?sa=t&amp;amp;rct=j&amp;amp;q=&amp;amp;esrc=s&amp;amp;source=web&amp;amp;cd=1&amp;amp;ved=0CJIBEBYwAA&amp;amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwdc.com%2Fen%2Fproducts%2Fproducts.aspx%3Fid%3D280&amp;amp;ei=4XMFUOHPFMPe0QGcgNHvCA&amp;amp;usg=AFQjCNGiw9MIZqTE5IgrLrtln_1YzSaiWw&amp;amp;sig2=iQNaUtC2Ls-RB8rRhlTggw">Western Digital My Book Live</a> creates a single location for everyone on your network to store files, including music, movies and photos. The device also lets you stream media to your entertainment center and access your files over the Internet from anywhere.</p>

<h2>Online Backup Services</h2>

<p>Several reputable, affordable online services let you put your data into their cloud. The advantage of this type of backup is that you can access data from any computer, anywhere theres an Internet connection. Prices are based on how much storage you need, and can rise quickly. But for those who travel a great deal or just want the assurance of additional backup, online storage is a compelling option.</p>

<p>
<strong>Example:</strong> 
<a href="http://www.google.com/url?sa=t&amp;amp;rct=j&amp;amp;q=&amp;amp;esrc=s&amp;amp;source=web&amp;amp;cd=1&amp;amp;ved=0CHIQFjAA&amp;amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.staples.com%2Fsbd%2Fcre%2Fmarketing%2Fcarbonite-online-backup%2Findex.html&amp;amp;ei=9HMFUIL4HqqB0QHw4cCgCA&amp;amp;usg=AFQjCNEGe1NNPB1ba3lGScVBnAs9niZFdQ&amp;amp;sig2=pPspHKbBzHoGU7f1NKbqqQ">Carbonite</a> offers a free trial for its service and has plans available for both home users and small business users. The company also provides tutorials on file backup and data recovery.</p>

<p>Staples offers Carbonite backup products in our stores and online at Staples.com as well. With our help, we can set up Carbonite products for your home office or small business.</p>

<p>Once you choose a backup option and your data is safe, then you can move on to other activities  like reminding everyone else to back up their data, too.</p>
]]></content></item>
